<paragraph id="DDFBAA0814C1D48874FF64219522D37E" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName id="ED9CB1045F2DCCFE3EDF2CCC28D62D78" authorityName="Guo &amp; Cheng &amp; Jiang &amp; Xue &amp; Han" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Guo &amp; Cheng &amp; Jiang &amp; Xue &amp; Han" baseAuthorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Deroca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Deroca crystalla" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crystalla" status="comb. nov.">Deroca crystalla</taxonomicName>
Chu &amp; Wang, 1987: 116. Holotype ♂, China: Yunnan: Lushui: Yaojiaping (IZCAS).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1BD2DC3C390CE8AD69152FEF65FE6443" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="notes">
<paragraph id="552033028EAD6FE1C4E703FD8318479E" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D2521F8DD844016D14B789AD73AD9EB2" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
The species 
<taxonomicName id="587968383A1E6EA5D7A36ED507F2391C" authorityName="Guo &amp; Cheng &amp; Jiang &amp; Xue &amp; Han" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Guo &amp; Cheng &amp; Jiang &amp; Xue &amp; Han" baseAuthorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Deroca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Deroca crystalla" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crystalla">
<emphasis id="A68B07598395DF3DCF8A26536C0EDFEB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Deroca crystalla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Chu &amp; Wang, 1987 was described from Yunnan, Sichuan and Tibet. Its male genitalia obviously belong to the 
<taxonomicName id="987E3C882DA572EF96781B499D386D5A" baseAuthorityName="Bryk" baseAuthorityYear="1943" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona derocina" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="derocina">
<emphasis id="6E870D376E11FA5C47B9A1E83F875125" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona derocina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group of 
<taxonomicName id="0B73CA6F80866BA5E33216F489876357" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1888" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="47669CD981D53FA237142BBAF37E70C4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and we therefore transfer the species to 
<taxonomicName id="43D9BE08AF75A508EBE16D365945ED9F" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1888" class="Insecta" family="Drepanidae" genus="Ditrigona" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ditrigona" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF4A49435FB11B1851E49EF4372F5D9F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Ditrigona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The male genitalia are almost identical to those of 
<taxonomicName id="F5C7BCA976BF0504E39FFBCE6B705509" family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. derocina" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="derocina">
<emphasis id="5A60610234D4B4459B9A9FBCDE886EA9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. derocina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the corpus bursae of the female genitalia is scobinate, which is different from the smooth ones of 
<taxonomicName id="DA33748AF3D8CCF8CCBF55FFBC99A15A" family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. derocina" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="derocina">
<emphasis id="DC5A2DFD9BE78ECB005CD14648F8F4D4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. derocina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="5477476CD8BA327F26A1647C5D2D6999" family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. diana" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="diana">
<emphasis id="C20992DB7CDE2B694232B5106A4EFCF6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. diana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, though they share a very long and narrow ductus bursae and a slender curved signum. The ostial plate is invisible in 
<taxonomicName id="1615C84AE1D66F49F917BDFB43348FA3" family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. crystalla" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="crystalla">
<emphasis id="9BB2A26042F7096FD0CEE8F7500AEC7C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. crystalla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and it is most probably present, though it seems that the sternite was incorrectly removed and the abdomen is not preserved on the slide.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
